# If you examine each independent attributes, description and their distribution above, several attributes are skewed.
# Independent attributes age and day have skewness values between 0 and 1, therefore these are not skewed.
# Independent attributes which are skewed to positive (right) are balance, duration, campaign, pdays and previous.
#These variables have a large tail to the right hand side of the distribution. 
# We see that pdays which is number of days that passed after the client was last contacted has extremely skewed distribution 
# with 75% values under -1. This attribute is further examined with respect to the Target attribute. 
# We find that more of the positive values of pdays are associated with yes in Target attribute

# There are unknowns in the data set for categorical attributes as follows:
# job - unknown 0.63% (insignificant)
# education - unknown 4% (insignificant)
# contact communication unknown 28.8% - There are only two real categories. It may be possible to assign the unknowns to 
#             the most prevalent category which is cellular, we will examine significant trends in bivariate analysis
# poutcome - unknown 81.75% outcome of the last campaign was not known for a large majority of the clients. Due to its
# significance we can leave this attribute alone. Success in poutcome is a good predictor of Term Deposit sale.

#Insight about Continous Independent Attributes
# age : Clients who have a broader spread appear to be more likely to opt for term deposit
# balance: When the outliers are ignored, we may see higher balance would predict higher chance of term deposit
# day: Higher value on no. of days since last campaign may be a good predictor for the term deposit
# duration: longer contact of duration is a good predictor of term deposit, but the original data set had special instruction
#           to drop this independent attribute, when this attribute was left in the model it dominated the decision tree
#           this attribute was dropped in the second run
# campaign does not appear to be a good predictor of term deposit
# pdays: High values of pdays highly predicts term deposit

## function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm2 = metrics.confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm2, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Conclusion¶

Performance metrics¶

Testing Accuracy The best Testing Accuracy of 0.907 was achieved by Random Forest and Catboosting algorithms. It is the fraction of all observations that were correctly classified by the model. Although there are other performance metrics of the models that are more important based on the business goal behind conducting the analysis.

  • precision Precision is a measure of a classifiers exactness. For each class, it is defined as the ratio of true positives to the sum of true and false positives. Said another way, for all instances classified positive, what percent was correct?. In this case the Random Forest and Catboosting algorithm provided the highest precision.

  • recall Recall is a measure of the classifiers completeness; the ability of a classifier to correctly find all positive instances. For each class, it is defined as the ratio of true positives to the sum of true positives and false negatives. Said another way, for all instances that were actually positive, what percent was classified correctly? In this case Bagging algorithm achieved the best Recall score.

  • f1 score The F1 score is a weighted harmonic mean of precision and recall such that the best score is 1.0 and the worst is 0.0. Generally speaking, F1 scores are lower than accuracy measures as they embed precision and recall into their computation. As a rule of thumb, the weighted average of F1 should be used to compare classifier models, not global accuracy.

Using F1 as the measure for comparing the models, the best F1 score of 0.746 was provided by Bagging algorithm, therefore it would be considered the best algorithm for this data set.¶

Observations of Label imbalance Significant imbalance was observed between Class 1 and 0. All models provided much better metrics for Class 0. Bagging algorithm provided higher f1 score of 0.559 and 0.949 for Classes 1 and 0 respectively. These were the highest f1 scores observed when compared to Ada Boost and Random Forest models. ROC and ROC/AUC data was observed and it was comparable or better for Bagging algorithm than other algorithms.
